<br>
You have no idea how right you are.  Sony, like all big businesses, run month to month on borrowed money using &quot;projected&quot; income as collateral.  If for one month they did not get their lunch money, there would be hell to pay, and they would shape the fuck up.<br>
<br>
I have been advocating this for a long time.  The problem is, people's addictions do run so high that they could not do it.  I know myself that I could not do it easily.  It would unfortunately take a major infraction such as days of server outages to anger enough people long enough to act.  Its like AOL with busy signals.  That would be a technical infraction.  So long as the grievances are a few lost items and the spin doctors are hard at work, you cant bring change from social injustices.<br>
<br>
On the note of AOL, right after they settled their class-action suit and added lots of numbers, their prices were jacked up.  It was a supposed &quot;inflation and operations fee increase&quot;.  Inflation does not move 10%/year and operating modems is spiralling down exponetially.  Who knows what Sony would do to spite us.  You dont piss off companies with more money than the state you live in.<br>
<br>
In another example of AOL, AOL used to have a volunteer neighborhood helper program.  (sound familiar?)  The volunteers eventually got tired of working for free and sued for backed wages owed for service they rendered.  They won.  The difference is there were thousands of them from all backgrounds instead of a few hundred guides in EQ who are pure internet junkies.<br>
<br>
